content.description:
Low angle terrain with smears to the first bolt. Horizontal pockets and ledges on occasional smears the rest of the way to the anchors below and left of a small juniper hanging out of the rock.

Moos means cat in my native language of Keres.
content.location: Just left of the 10-foot oval concavity in the wall 20 feet up. It's 10 feet left of Be'sho that ascends the column between the 10-foot concavity in the wall and the 30-foot concavity.

content.description:
Straightforward start to a good stance then thin pockets, pinches to a less-than-satisfying horizontal seam. The bulge above requires more moves on minute pockets and ledges with smears for the feet. There is a break on good stances just above before the crux, which is really thin fingers and crimps with minimal feet (awkward smears). The horizontal seam just above the crux is basically a long sloper so have fun with that! Above the last stance is a final moderate bulge.

Le'ch means rabbit in my native language of Keres.
content.location: The dark gray bulges to the right of Ki'yatni that has the pale pink rock below.

content.description:
Funky climb connecting the slanted cracks in the limestone to slopers above.

Start on featured, easy terrain to a slightly overhung pod that provides pockets and crimps to access the sharp, slanting cracks.

After about 10-12 feet on the cracks, veer up and to the right on small pockets and crimps with hard-to-see foot holds and smears (crux).

Ku'hi means bear in my native language of Keres.
content.protection: 6 bolts to 2-bolt anchor. The first bolt is likely unnecessary given the good stance directly above it.
content.location: Far left of the wall. The start is 30 feet left of the juniper tree and ascends to the anchors just right of the juniper tree on the ledge.

content.description:
Ledges and smears to the right of the bush 15 feet up. The first bolt is below and to the right of the bush. Mantle onto the ledge and ascend the left-facing dihedral that good features until smears and crimps are required to get to another second sloping ledge. The terrain eases up a bit to the left. Watch out for the dead cactus near the top.

Ki'yatni means deer in my native language of Keres.
content.location: To the right of Ki'yami and a child-sized bush on the first sloping ledge above. The pink pale rock (crux) is down and to the right of the bush.

content.description:
Fairly easy terrain at first until the pod is reached, which requires some stemming and smearing on crimps. A ledge is reached then easier terrain is up and to the left but feet are mostly smears as you hold onto minute pockets and crimps.

Ki'yami means eagle in my native language of Keres.
content.location: Just right, if not behind the juniper tree.

content.description:
Thin pockets, crimps on smears and tiny ledges. The crux is the second bulge over yellow-orange rock.

Cac'an means naughty or poorly behaved in my native tongue of Keres.
content.location: Just left (almost behind the juniper) on the wall.

content.description: Low-angled terrain to the first clip below the 10-foot oval concavity. Solid pockets and ledges follow the left side of the column between the oval concavities. Crimpy terrain leads to a high step with a pinch to attain the next ledge. More thin edges to the top.
content.location: Ascends the column between the two concavities toward the right side of the formation.
